# API Integration Guide for Contract Verification

Based on my analysis of the codebase, here are detailed answers to your questions about the API and how to handle ABI data correctly:

## 1. ABI Data Format

The ABI data from the `/contracts/{address}/abi` endpoint is returned in the following format:

```json
{
  "address": "0x1234567890123456789012345678901234567890",
  "abi": [
    {
      "constant": true,
      "inputs": [],
      "name": "name",
      "outputs": [{"name": "", "type": "string"}],
      "payable": false,
      "stateMutability": "view",
      "type": "function"
    },
    // More ABI entries...
  ]
}
```

The response is an object with two properties:
- `address`: The contract address
- `abi`: An array of ABI objects representing the contract's functions, events, etc.

When processing this response, you should extract the `abi` property which is the actual array of ABI objects:

```javascript
// Example of correctly extracting the ABI array
async function getContractABI(address) {
  try {
    const response = await axios.get(`${API_URL}/contracts/${address}/abi`);

    // The ABI is in the 'abi' property of the response
    const abiArray = response.data.abi;

    // Now you can use this array to filter read/write functions, etc.
    return abiArray;
  } catch (error) {
    console.error('Error fetching ABI:', error);
    throw error;
  }
}
```

## 2. Contract Details Properties

For contract details, you should display the following properties from the `/contracts/{address}` endpoint:

```json
{
  "address": "0x1234567890123456789012345678901234567890",
  "creatorAddress": "0xabcdef1234567890abcdef1234567890abcdef12",
  "ownerAddress": "0x0987654321fedcba0987654321fedcba09876543",
  "blockNumber": 12345678,
  "timestamp": 1616161616,
  "transactionHash": "0xabcdef1234567890abcdef1234567890abcdef1234567890abcdef1234567890",
  "contractType": "ERC20",
  "name": "My Token",
  "symbol": "MTK",
  "decimals": 18,
  "totalSupply": "1000000000000000000000000",
  "balance": "0",
  "verified": true,
  "compilerVersion": "0.8.0",
  "optimizationUsed": true,
  "runs": 200,
  "evmVersion": "cancun",
  "verifiedAt": "2025-03-28T10:00:00Z"
}
```

The most important properties to display are:
- `name`: Contract name
- `symbol`: Token symbol (if applicable)
- `contractType`: Type of contract (ERC20, ERC721, ERC1155, or UNKNOWN)
- `creatorAddress`: Address that deployed the contract
- `blockNumber`: Block where the contract was deployed
- `timestamp`: Timestamp of contract deployment
- `compilerVersion`: Solidity compiler version used
- `optimizationUsed`: Whether optimization was used
- `runs`: Number of optimization runs
- `evmVersion`: EVM version used for compilation
- `verifiedAt`: When the contract was verified

For token contracts, also display:
- `decimals`: Number of decimals (for ERC20)
- `totalSupply`: Total supply of tokens

## 3. Read and Write Functions

There is no specific endpoint for getting read and write functions separately. Instead, you should filter the ABI array from the `/contracts/{address}/abi` endpoint based on the function properties:

```javascript
function parseABI(abiArray) {
  // Filter read functions (view/pure)
  const readFunctions = abiArray.filter(item => 
    item.type === 'function' && 
    (item.stateMutability === 'view' || item.stateMutability === 'pure' || item.constant === true)
  );

  // Filter write functions (non-view/pure)
  const writeFunctions = abiArray.filter(item => 
    item.type === 'function' && 
    item.stateMutability !== 'view' && 
    item.stateMutability !== 'pure' && 
    !item.constant
  );

  // Filter events
  const events = abiArray.filter(item => 
    item.type === 'event'
  );

  return { readFunctions, writeFunctions, events };
}
```

For older Solidity versions, functions might use `constant: true` instead of `stateMutability: "view"`, so check both properties.

